WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:06.300
One pumping well disturbed the Madison aquifer for about seven days. Five observation wells recorded the response across more than three kilometres.

00:06.300 --> 00:12.500
In the classical radial relation, flux and the drawdown gradient are evaluated at the same radius and time. The model therefore keeps one constitutive clock.

00:12.500 --> 00:18.700
A connected fracture can carry flow quickly while a dead-end branch takes longer to exchange pressure. This is a proposed interpretation of another response time.

00:18.700 --> 00:24.900
The generalized relation assigns one response time to radial flux and another to the drawdown gradient.

00:24.900 --> 00:31.200
Substituting that relation into radial mass conservation changes the aquifer equation itself; it is not a delay added after calculation.

00:31.200 --> 00:37.800
The boundary-value problem is transformed in time. The well and far-field conditions select a modified-Bessel radial solution in the Laplace domain.

00:37.800 --> 00:44.300
For each observation well, the study estimated three hydraulic parameters and two lag times using Levenberg-Marquardt nonlinear least squares.

00:44.300 --> 00:51.000
Table 2 reports lower Case 2 standard error at four wells. CHLN-2 is equal at the reported precision.

00:51.000 --> 00:57.500
The fitted lags do not collapse to one site constant. Figure 5 reports distance trends after excluding BHPL because it lies opposite the pumping well.

00:57.500 --> 01:04.200
Lagging Theory is therefore a testable pumping-test diagnostic. Its fitted lags remain conditioned on the model, test design, distance, and site structure.
